briefdescription.para: List of all tokens recognized by the interpreter.

detaileddescription.para: Note that built-in function names are not considered tokens. Instead, they are treated like user-defined functions, but with hardcoded handlers rather than being redirected to user-defined code.

The following #define generates an enum of token types, along with a corresponding array of string representations for each token. These are used in basic.c to perform tokenization during program parsing.

memberdef.name: EMIT_STMT
memberdef.initializer: static const int kw_##name __attribute__((section(".kw." #name), used)) = name;

briefdescription.para: All tokens recognised by the interpreter. Note that built in function names are NOT tokens, they are parsed like user functions, just with a hard coded handler instead of redirecting into the user program.

detaileddescription.para: The #define below builds an enum, and can also build an array of strings of the names in the enum, which is built and used within basic.c for tokenization.

memberdef.type: *brief Initialise tokenizer **param program program text *param ctx context *void
